{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01L2P5Rn7ZQCMr3hBqWsK7QG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So the build system uses HTTP to talk to a builder service sidecar at `http://{domain}:8080`. The domain is resolved via DNS. The \"Read timed out\" error is from the HTTP polling step where it polls `/status/{job_id}` with a 10-second timeout. But the actual build has a 3600s timeout, and poll returns `None` on timeout.\n\nLooking at line 480-481:\n```python\nif result is None:\n    (response_dir / \"retcode\").write_text(\"1\")\n    (response_dir / \"stderr.log\").write_text(\"Builder unavailable or timed out\")\n```\n\nBut the stderr.log says `UnixHTTPConnectionPool(host='localhost', port=None): Read timed out.` which is a different message than \"Builder unavailable or timed out\". \n\nLooking at the error: `UnixHTTPConnectionPool(host='localhost', port=None)` - this is a Unix socket HTTP connection, not a regular HTTP connection. This suggests it's connecting to a Docker socket (`/var/run/docker.sock`) somewhere in the chain.\n\nThe \"Read timed out\" with 10s timeout suggests that during the polling phase, the GET /status/{job_id} call is failing with a connection error (from the builder sidecar connecting to Docker), and the error message is being propagated back.\n\nActually, looking at the error handling code, connection errors during polling just get logged and retried. So the \"Read timed out\" message must be coming from the builder sidecar itself when it tries to connect to Docker before any rebuild_id is assigned, and that error gets written to stderr.log.\n\nThis suggests the Docker daemon is either having connectivity issues or is overloaded, preventing the builder sidecar from communicating with it. Let me check if there's a rebuild_id saved from a previous successful build that I can reference.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage"